Hello, reader,

If you don't know what the OSI (computer science acronym) is, then this will probably be irrelevant until you have at least a basic understanding of it.

If you have no idea what it is, read about it first. If you've at least seen a diagram of the OSI model on DuckDuckGo or another search engine, then feel free to continue.

For too long there hasn't been a de facto way to get your coding "chi" back after taking a break from programming (say, more than 14 days). This challenge can also help improve your general programming skills (and yes... even in the age of AI).

Here's the challenge:

Write "Hello, World."

Simple, right? Just "Hello, World." But I want you to really write "Hello, World." Think about the OSI model and the entire software stack (look that up now if you want, although it's not essential if you're a complete beginner).

Give yourself a time limit—15, 30, or 60 minutes—and complete the challenge in any three programming languages you like, plus at least one shell (sh) or Bash script. Be as creative as you can with such a simple program, including as many programming concepts as possible.

I'll admit that if you're a true beginner (less than 6–12 years into computers), this exercise may not seem particularly useful yet. However, its value tends to increase over time as your experience grows.

Be sure to use the shell (or Bash) script to compile or interpret your programs, execute them, remove the generated files from the temporary directory (see the repository structure), and then have the script remove itself when it's finished.

There's also a text file containing lower-level code examples (such as binary, if you've heard of it). I may add a Windows version in the future. I'm not entirely sure how that will work yet, but I'll figure it out. For now, enjoy this version.

